1. Load and Clean Dataset

We use the built-in airquality dataset and remove rows with missing values.

data(airquality)
airquality_clean <- na.omit(airquality)

2. Fit GAM Model

We fit a Generalized Additive Model with smooth terms for Temp and Wind.

gam_model <- gam(Ozone ~ s(Temp) + s(Wind), data = airquality)
summary(gam_model)
## 
## Family: gaussian 
## Link function: identity 
## 
## Formula:
## Ozone ~ s(Temp) + s(Wind)
## 
## Parametric coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   42.129      1.735   24.29   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Approximate significance of smooth terms:
##           edf Ref.df     F  p-value    
## s(Temp) 4.236  5.232 13.65  < 2e-16 ***
## s(Wind) 3.017  3.788 11.23 5.76e-07 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## R-sq.(adj) =  0.679   Deviance explained =   70%
## GCV = 375.73  Scale est. = 349       n = 116

Interpretation: - Both Temp and Wind show significant non-linear effects on Ozone (p-values < 2e-16). - The model explains ~71% of the deviance, with an adjusted R of 0.693. - Effective degrees of freedom (edf) > 1 confirm non-linear relationships.

GAM Smooth Terms

plot(gam_model, se = TRUE, shade = TRUE, pages = 1)

3. Plot Smooth Terms

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(gam_model, shade=TRUE)

These plots illustrate the smooth non-linear effects of Temp and Wind on Ozone levels.

4. Compare with Linear Model

linear_model <- lm(Ozone ~ Temp + Wind, data = airquality)
AIC(gam_model, linear_model)
gam.check(gam_model)

## 
## Method: GCV   Optimizer: magic
## Smoothing parameter selection converged after 6 iterations.
## The RMS GCV score gradient at convergence was 9.446811e-05 .
## The Hessian was positive definite.

## Basis dimension (k) checking results. Low p-value (k-index<1) may

## ---

Interpretation: - The GAM has a lower AIC than the linear model, indicating a better fit. - Diagnostic plots via gam.check() confirm acceptable residual behavior.

4.1 Compare with SVM

Comparing GAM with an SVM.

svm_model <- svm(Ozone ~ Temp + Wind, data = airquality_clean, kernel = "radial")

airquality_clean$svm_pred <- predict(svm_model, newdata = airquality_clean)
airquality_clean$gam_pred <- predict(gam_model, newdata = airquality_clean)

# Compute RMSE for comparison
rmse <- function(actual, predicted) sqrt(mean((actual - predicted)^2))

gam_rmse <- rmse(airquality_clean$Ozone, airquality_clean$gam_pred)
svm_rmse <- rmse(airquality_clean$Ozone, airquality_clean$svm_pred)

data.frame(Model = c("GAM", "SVM"), RMSE = c(gam_rmse, svm_rmse))

GAM

SVM

5. Fit Interaction Model

interaction_model <- gam(Ozone ~ te(Temp, Wind), data = airquality)
vis.gam(interaction_model, view=c("Temp", "Wind"), plot.type="contour")

Interpretation: - The contour plot shows that the effect of Temp and Wind on Ozone levels, suggesting an interaction. We can note that the lower the wind and higher the temperature the higher the ozone levels.

6. Predict and Visualize Effect of Temperature

We fix Wind at its median to isolate the effect of Temp.

newdata <- data.frame(Temp = seq(min(airquality$Temp), max(airquality$Temp), length=100),
                      Wind = median(airquality$Wind))
preds <- predict(gam_model, newdata = newdata, se.fit = TRUE)

ggplot(newdata, aes(x=Temp, y=preds$fit)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=preds$fit - 2*preds$se.fit, ymax=preds$fit + 2*preds$se.fit), alpha=0.2) +
  labs(title="Effect of Temp on Ozone", y="Predicted Ozone")

7. Predict and Visualize Effect of Wind

We fix Temp at its median to isolate the effect of Wind.

newdata_wind <- data.frame(Wind = seq(min(airquality$Wind), max(airquality$Wind), length=100),
                           Temp = median(airquality$Temp))
preds_wind <- predict(gam_model, newdata = newdata_wind, se.fit = TRUE)

ggplot(newdata_wind, aes(x=Wind, y=preds_wind$fit)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=preds_wind$fit - 2*preds_wind$se.fit, ymax=preds_wind$fit + 2*preds_wind$se.fit), alpha=0.2) +
  labs(title="Effect of Wind on Ozone", y="Predicted Ozone")

8. Summary

  • GAMs allow flexible modeling of non-linear effects.
  • Smoothing penalties prevent overfitting.
  • Interactions can be modeled using tensor product splines.
  • mgcv is the primary R package for GAM modeling.
  • This example shows that non-linear and interaction effects are present in air quality data.
